{ Black's choice to take on e4 defines the Open Spanish. Black has enough resources to hold on if he knows what he is doing, but White will easily win back the pawn as well as get some initiative. }
6. d4
{ It is important to remember that in almost all cases, if Black takes on e4 before castling, White should try to open up the position with the central strike d2-d4. In this position, Black usually follows up with 6...b5 followed by 7...d5, but there are some interesting sideline continuations as well. As stated earlier, these positions are much easier to play as White since Black is playing risky chess by grabbing material before castling. }
