1. e4 e5
{ 1...e5 is the most classical way for Black to play, controlling the center and opening up lines for his pieces. Since Black is down a tempo in an otherwise symmetrical position, White will be able to fight for the initiative rather easily. }
2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black protects his e5-pawn and brings a minor piece of his own into the game. }
3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ 4.♗xc6 is also a viable option, but 4.♗a4 keeps the bishop pair and keeps more options open for both sides. }
4... Nf6 { Black attacks the e4-pawn and develops another minor piece. } 5. O-O
Be7
{ The Closed Spanish is the most popular way for Black to play because it is quite difficult to survive in the sharp, open positions that arise after 5...♘xe4 6.d4. Note that by blocking the e-file, Black actually threatens to take on e4 and win a pawn. }
6. Re1
{ White protects his e4-pawn with his rook because he does not want to obstruct his long-term plan of c2-c3 followed by d2-d4. For example, 6.Nc3 would block the c3-square while 6.d3 would be a bit too slow  (although it is still a perfectly viable option if White seeks a slow game)  . }
6... b5
{ Black kicks back White's bishop to facilitate further development. A careless move such as 6...O-O would allow 7.♗xc6 followed by 8.♘xe5, winning a pawn. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ By playing ...d6, Black supports his e5-pawn. Black is now threatening to play 8...Na5, winning the bishop pair. }
8. c3
{ White prepares to meet ...Na5 with Bc2 and looks to gain a solid stake in the center with d2-d4. }
8... O-O
{ Black castles. Note that 8...♗g4, pinning the knight, is not a good choice for strategic reasons. Those reasons will be explained in the theory chapter. }
9. h3
{ White takes a moment to stop ...Bg4, which would pressure White's center if White had played 9.d4. White is behind in development, but with the center closed, White has time to catch up. Black is well developed, but Nc6  (restricted by c3 and blocking Black's c pawn)  and Be7  (trapped inside Black's pawn chain)  are passively placed. Therefore, Black is likely to spend some time improving those pieces  (...Na5 or ...Nb8-Nd7, ...Re8 with ...Bf8 and ...g6 with ...Bg7 are common ideas)  , which gives White enough time to finish his development and play d2-d4. White usually aims to exploit his superior center  (it will be superior after White plays d2-d4)  and space advantage by fighting for the initiative. }
