{ This game was played in 1858. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Bg4
{ 3...Bg4 is a weak move. 3...exd4, 3...Nd7 or 3...Nf6 are stronger. } 4. dxe5
{ Black is forced to make a concession. } 4... Bxf3
{ Black agrees to give White a development advantage and the bishop pair. 4...dxe5 loses a pawn to 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 6.Nxe5 }
5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4
{ White is ahead on development so he fights for the initiative. Every move that White makes for the rest of the game is either a forcing move  (Check, capture, threat)  or a developing move. }
6... Nf6
{ Black defends against White's threat of 7.Qxf7# and develops a piece. However, this isn't best due to White's reply. 6...Qf6 is stronger. }
7. Qb3 { Double-threat ! Threat 1: 8.Qxb7. Threat 2: 8.Bxf7+ Kd7 9.Qe6#. } 7...
Qe7 8. Nc3
{ White chooses to develop a piece instead of winning a pawn with 8.Qxb7 because 8...Qb4+ forces White to trade queens. Usually, the side with the initiative prefers to keep queens on the board because they are powerful attackers. }
8... c6
{ Defending against the threat of Qxb7, but Black is getting dangerously behind in development. }
9. Bg5
{ White pins Nf6 and prepares to castle queenside. Black can hardly develop his pieces: Nf6 is pinned, Qe7 blocks Bf8 from escaping, ...Nd7 loses to Qxb7. }
9... b5
{ Black attempts to force White to retreat one of his attacking pieces in order to get some breathing room. }
10. Nxb5
{ White sacrifices a piece for 2 pawns. He is playing according to the principle 'You should try to open the position when you have a lead in development'. This principle is usually true because the side with more pieces out is usually better prepared to handle the newly opened files and diagonals. }
10... cxb5 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. O-O-O
{ Both of Black's knights are pinned. White is threatening to take on d7 because both recaptures lose Black's queen. }
12... Rd8 { Black adds a defender to his d7 knight. } 13. Rxd7
{ White sacrifices the exchange, but can immediately win it back because when Black recaptures with his rook, White can play 14. Rhd1 attacking it again. Black is still pinned when he recaptures, and he has no time to bring other pieces to defend.   Doubling rooks with  13.Rd3  followed by  14.Rhd1  is also strong }
13... Rxd7 14. Rd1 Qe6
{ White was threatening to take on d7, so Black offers a queen trade. } 15.
Bxd7+
{ White starts a forcing sequence of moves that end in checkmate. It shouldn't be a surprise that such a combination exists in the position because White is attacking with all of his pieces. }
15... Nxd7 { 15...Qxd7 loses the queen to 16.Rxd7. } 16. Qb8+
{ 16.Rd8 would be checkmate if Nd7 was gone, so White sacrifices his queen to force it to unblock the d-file. }
16... Nxb8 17. Rd8#
{ A brilliant game illustrating the importance of development and the initiative. }
