{ The Berlin endgame. Black has a poor pawn structure and can't castle, while White is ahead in development and has a safe king. As compensation for these positional advantages, Black has the bishop pair. @@StartBlockQuote@@'Every time the Berlin endgame shows up on the board, everyone starts to cry quietly, because such positions are boring. However, games are often full of exciting play, although there are no queens.' - GM Vladimir Kramnik. @@EndBlockQuote@@@@StartBlockQuote@@'At a basic level, the battle will revolve around two major positional elements. The first is Black's ability @@StartBracket@@ or lack thereof @@EndBracket@@ to hold his own on the kingside. The knight on f5 looks solid enough - after all, it is way too early for g4 - but a later g2-g4 followed by f2-f4 and even f4-f5 can decide the game in White's favor. Black will have to be very careful to develop his pieces in such a way as to render g2-g4 harmless, and to halt White's general progress on the kingside. The second element is White's ability @@StartBracket@@or, once again, lack thereof@@EndBracket@@ to effect favorable piece trades. In general, due to Black's crippled pawn structure, trades favor White, although this is not always the case. Frequently, a trade of dark-squared bishops will serve to accentuate the structural weaknesses in Black's position, especially if he has played ...h5.' - GM Daniel Naroditsky@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
9. h3
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@'For most of the Berlin Variation's existence, 9.Nc3 was considered to be the only move, and understandably so. After all, White's queenside is still entirely undeveloped. However, there is actually no pressing need to develop immediately, and in recent years, the more flexible 9.h3 has become very popular. In fact, h3 is more of a healthy waiting move than anything else: White improves his position and waits for Black to lay his cards on the table. Only after Black chooses a system of development will he decide whether or not to develop the knight to c3.' - GM Daniel Naroditsky@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
9... Bd7 { Black prepares to bring his king to the queenside. } 10. Rd1
{ Pinning Bd7. White is threatening to play g4 followed by e6 ! and Ne5. }
