{ Black unpins Bd7 to defend against White's threat.   10...Be7  Black prepares to meet  g4  with  ...Nh4.  11.g4  Nh4  12.Nxh4  gives White a slight advantage because he can rapidly develop his pieces  (Nd2-f3 chases away Bh4)  (and double rooks on the d-file. Black might be able to draw with best play, but White is the one pressing.) }
11. g4 Ne7 12. Ng5 Be8
{ 12...Be6  13.Nxe6  wins the bishop pair and further damages Black's pawn structure by creating an isolated pawn. }
13. f4
{ White has the initiative.  @@StartBlockQuote@@'Black is fine from an objective standpoint, but even strong Grandmasters have found it difficult to successfully wade through the ensuing tactical complexities.' - GM Daniel Naroditsky@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
