{ A fianchetto setup is quite logical at this moment because Black should try to fianchetto his light-squared bishop on the queenside due to the pawn on e6. Black will have difficulties doing so if there is a dangerous bishop of White's on g2 eyeing the long diagonal. }
5... Ngf6
{ Black develops his kingside knight and offers a trade to reduce his spacial cramp. }
6. Nxf6+
{ White does not really have a good retreat square for the knight, so he trades it off. }
6... Nxf6 { Black recaptures, avoiding any structural problems. } 7. Bg2
{ White establishes his bishop on the important h1-a8 diagonal. } *

