{ Black's main problem piece in the Rubenstein variation of the French is his light-squared bishop. To activate his light-squared bishop, Black usually wants to play a queenside fianchetto because his e6-pawn restricts him from developing his light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Therefore, White aims to beat Black to the long diagonal and apply long-term pressure to his queenside. }
7... c5
{ Black challenges White's space advantage. Alternatives will be covered in the theory section. }
8. Bg2
{ White allows Black to capture on d4 and increases his lead in development. }
8... cxd4 { The only consistent follow-up to 7...c5. } 9. Qxd4
{ White is fine with a queen trade for multiple reasons. He would have long-term pressure on the long-diagonal against Black's queenside, especially since ...Qxd4 Nxd4 would unblock White's light-squared bishop. In the endgames, piece activity is very important, and White has more active pieces and easier development. Black still is a long ways from activating his light-squared bishop, and it will only get harder if the queens are traded. }
9... Qxd4
{ Since White has such a massive lead in development, Black's best chance of fighting for equality is accepting the queen trade, otherwise White's initiative might quickly grow to a decisive attack. }
10. Nxd4
{ This is one of the main tabiyas of the 5.g3 variation of the Rubenstein. To take stock of the position: White has more active pieces, can easily finish his development, and has a queenside pawn majority. White also has pressure against Black's queenside. Black has a solid but passive pawn structure and can quickly develop his kingside, but due to the pressure against his b7-pawn, has trouble developing his queenside. At master level, virtually all of the games from this position end in a White win or a draw, but Black has virtually no winning chances due to his passive position. }
10... Bc5
{ Black hopes to gain a tempo in order to give himself more time to untangle. }
11. Nb3
{ White wins the tempo back and unblocks the d-file. White can either double rooks on the d-file or simply centralize both of his rooks, as the center is open. }
11... Bd6
{ 11...Bb6 is a natural alternative and will be covered in the theory section. }
12. Be3
{ White now has significant pressure on Black's queenside pawns and can easily finish his development with O-O-O and Rhe1. }
12... O-O 13. O-O-O Bc7
{ Black retreats his bishop rather than self-pin with ...Rd8, which would give White a reason to double his rooks on the d-file. }
14. Bc5
{ White takes advantage of the newly weakened diagonal and attacks Black's rook. }
14... Re8
{ 14...Rd8 would allow the trade of rooks, which favors White. This is because he could  (after trading rooks)  follow up with Rd1 with domination on the d-file. }
15. Rhe1
{ White finishes his development with a harmonious game. If Black waits, White could increase the pressure by improving his worst piece: Nb3-d2-c4-d6. }
15... h6
{ Black can't safely develop his queenside. ...Bd7 drops a pawn to Bxb7, ...Rb8  (defending his b7-pawn)  loses the a7-pawn to Bxb7. Black has no good plan while White can increase the pressure.   15...a6  prepares  ...Rb8  , but weakens the dark-squares. White can take advantage of this with  Bd6  , trading dark-squared bishops, though he doesn't have to do this right away: White still has the time to keep making improvement moves such as  f4  because  ...Rb8  can always be met by  Ba7. }
16. Nd2 { White prepares a knight maneuver to d6. } 16... Nd7 17. Ba3 Nf6
{ Black can't do much but wait. } 18. Nc4 a5 19. Nd6 Bxd6 20. Bxd6
{ White now has the bishop pair on top of his superior piece activity and Black's weak queenside. }
20... Ra6 { Black fights for some activity, but it amounts to nothing. } 21.
Bf1 Ra8
{ 21...Rb6  22.Bc7  followed by  23.Bxa5  wins a pawn.   21...Rc6  22.Bb5  wins the exchange. }
22. Be5
{ White's plan is to now strengthen his position and coordinate his rooks down the d-file. }
22... b6
{ Black takes advantage of White's bishop  (finally !)  going off of the critical long-diagonal, but White quickly takes advantage of the weakened light-squares. }
23. Bb5 Rf8 24. Rd6
{ White now targets Black's weak b6-pawn. In this type of endgame, White often is able to win at least one of Black's queenside pawns in the long-run because Black will often remain passive if he doesn't make a queenside weakness to finish his development. }
24... Ba6
{ 24...Rb8  doesn't help: Black now has no safe square for his bishop to develop. White can win the b6-pawn at any time with Bd4-xb6, but White also has the time to gain space with moves like  f4  ,  a4  , and  c4  , because Black can't do much but wait. }
25. Rxb6 Bxb5 26. Rxb5
{ White is now ahead a pawn. Due to White's 3 vs. 1 queenside pawn majority, Black's weak a6-pawn, and White's superior piece activity, White's position is won. }
26... Nd5 27. a4 Rfc8 28. b3
{ White consolidates his queenside structure and prepares to target Black's isolated a5-pawn. }
