1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann Defense is one of the most solid ways for Black to play against 1.e4. He plans to strike against White's center next with ...d5. }
2. d4 { White seizes the center. } 2... d5
{ Black strikes back in the center. Not doing so would leave him in a very passive position due to his lack of space. }
3. e5
{ White gains space in the center. This is known as the Advance Variation and is the most ambitious way of playing against the Caro-Kann. The Advance Variation is stronger in the Caro-Kann than in the French because if Black challenges White's center with ...c5, he will have to lose a tempo because he already played ...c6. }
3... c5 { Black challenges White's center. } 4. dxc5
{ White captures Black's hanging pawn. } 4... e6
{ Black aims to recapture his c5-pawn. } 5. a3 Nc6
{ Capturing White's c5-pawn with 5...Bxc5 is likely to transpose after 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.b4, though White would have the additional option of meeting ...Bxc5 with Qg4 due to the delay of Nf3. }
6. Nf3
{ Now that ...Bg4 is impossible, it makes sense to protect White's e5-pawn, especially since 6.b4 is well met by 6...a5 ! }
6... Bxc5 7. b4 { White gains a tempo and prepares to play Bb2. } 7... Bb6 8.
Bb2
{ White is over-protecting his e5-pawn and can finish his development with Bd3, O-O, Re1, Nd2 and can open the position with c4. Black has a rather passive position because of his blocked in light-squared bishop and space disadvantage. }
