1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian is one of Black's most dynamic options against 1.e4. Black controls the d4-square with his c-pawn instead of his e-pawn, aiming to create an imbalance in pawn majorities if White plays d4. }
2. Nf3
{ White develops and plans to open the center with d2-d4. Black now has a variety of setups, which can be placed into different Sicilian families: the Dragon  (setups with ...g6)  , the Najdorf  (the most popular)  , the e6-Sicilians, the Classical, and the Sveshnikov/Kalashnikov  (these involve an early ...e5)  . There are also various sidelines to be explored. Due to the vast nature of Black's options, the Sicilian is a theoretical monster and will take up a large chunk of this repertoire. }
2... d6
{ 2...d6 fights for control of the e5-square so that Black can play ...Nf6 without having to worry about e4-e5 ideas. }
3. d4
{ The d2-d4 push is known as the Open Sicilian. White opens up the position to highlight his development advantage. Using the open lines that are created, White can often get a powerful initiative. }
3... cxd4
{ Black trades his c-pawn for White's d-pawn, creating a central majority. } 4.
Nxd4
{ White recaptures the pawn and establishes a strong knight on d4. 4.Nxd4 is the most natural recapture as 4.Qxd4 would allow Black to develop and gain time on the queen with 4...Nc6. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops with tempo. } 5. Nc3
{ White develops a piece and protects his d4-pawn. } 5... a6
{ The Najdorf. Black makes a useful waiting move by controlling the b5-square, preventing Bb5+ and preparing ...b5. Black can choose his system of development depending on how White responds. }
6. Bc4
{ 6.Bc4 is known as the Fischer-Sozin Attack and is one of the most aggressive ways of playing against the Najdorf. White wants to develop his pieces rapidly and can castle either direction. The Fischer-Sozin is not as popular as the English Attack or 6.Bg5, so many players underestimate it. }
