{ White takes advantage of the newly available g6-square and can sometimes sacrifice on f7.   18.Qh4  Nd7  19.Rh3  looks dangerous, but Black is able to survive  (for now)  after  19...h5  20.gxh6  Kh7. }
18... Kh8
{ Black's only move which doesn't immediately lose by force.   18...Kg7  19.Qf3   18...Bxh6  19.Qxh6 }
19. Qh4
{ White retreats his queen. He plans on continuing the attack with Rh3 and Ng4. }
19... b4
{ Black begins a counter-attack on the queenside. If he doesn't play actively, he will quickly lose on the kingside. }
20. Rh3
{ White should not retreat his c3-knight because then Black could safely capture White's d5-bishop  (Nxd5 would not be possible)  . White should focus on his kingside attack as Black is very exposed there and White has many attackers. }
20... bxc3
{ The only consistent reaction. If Black doesn't try to win material here, White will have a powerful attack for free.   20...exd5  21.Nxd5 }
21. Ng4 { White threatens Qxh7# and prepares Nf6. } 21... f5
{ Black defends his h7-pawn laterally. } 22. Nf6
{ White's knight heads to the f6-outpost and renews the threat of Qxh7+. }
22... cxb2+
{ The addition of ...cxb2 before playing ...h6 does not favor Black because White can hide his king behind Black's b2-pawn  (it adds protection because Black can't capture his own pawn)  . }
23. Kb1
{ White hides behind Black's pawn. White has a powerful attack. 23.Kxb2 and 23.Kd2 are also playable but only good enough for equality because they give Black more attacking resources. }
23... h6 24. Bxc5 { White removes the defender of the e6-pawn. } 24... dxc5
{ 24...exd5 is stronger. } 25. Bxe6
{ White has too many threats for Black to deal with: Qxh6+, gxf5, Rd7, among others. White has a decisive attack. }
