1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ 4...a6 signifies the Kan variation. Black intends on playing ...b5. } 5. c4
{ White gains space in the center before playing Nc3, impeding Black's ...d5 and ...b5 breaks. This pawn structure is most likely going to transpose into the Hedgehog pawn structure and is different from the Maroczy bind as Black is usually not going to fianchetto his kingside bishop  (he played ...e6 instead of ...g6)  . This leads to some key differences: since Black isn't pressuring the d4-knight, his plan in the mainline Maroczy bind  (...Nxd4 with ...Bc6, pressure on long-diagonal)  is no longer viable. Instead, Black generally wants to place his pawns on a6, b6, d6, and e6 in order to guard key central squares and intends to develop his pieces in a harmonious way which exerts pressure on White's center. He hopes that White will prematurely attack, where Black's pieces will be well-placed for a counter-attack. Black isn't forced to go for the Hedgehog plan, but it's his best chance for counterplay in the 5.c4 variation. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White defends his e4-pawn. Now that the e4-square is defended by a piece, White is threatening to play e5. }
6... Bb4
{ Black plays very aggressively, pinning White's c3-knight, intending to capture White's e4-pawn next. This approach is not as sound as developing his bishop to e7 because White has a lead in development and more space, so he is better prepared for potential complications which can occur. Black is welcome to retreat his bishop after White plays an eventual f3, but then he would have lost a tempo. }
7. Qd3
{ White defends his e4-pawn with his queen. This is the most aggressive approach because in some variations  (where Black has played ...Qc7)  White would like to recapture on c3 with his queen. 7.Qd3 is also more aggressive than 7.f3 because 7.Qd3 develops a piece. Now that White is controlling the e4-square, he is threatening to play e5  (gaining space with tempo)  . }
7... d5
{ Black opens the center. This approach favors White due to his lead in development. }
8. exd5
{ White opens the e-file and relieves any pressure that Black had on White's e4-pawn. }
8... exd5 9. Be2
{ White's position is slightly better due to his superior center control. White's plan is to castle, develop his dark-squared bishop, and centralize all of his pieces with a harmonious game. Black is behind on development with inferior piece coordination, he still has some problems to solve. }
