{ White gains space in the center before playing Nc3, impeding Black's ...d5 and ...b5 breaks. This pawn structure is most likely going to transpose into the Hedgehog pawn structure and is different from the Maroczy bind as Black is usually not going to fianchetto his kingside bishop  (he played ...e6 instead of ...g6)  . This leads to some key differences: since Black isn't pressuring the d4-knight, his plan in the mainline Maroczy bind  (...Nxd4 with ...Bc6, pressure on long-diagonal)  is no longer viable. Instead, Black generally wants to place his pawns on a6, b6, d6, and e6 in order to guard key central squares and intends to develop his pieces in a harmonious way which exerts pressure on White's center. He hopes that White will prematurely attack, where Black's pieces will be well-placed for a counter-attack. Black isn't forced to go for the Hedgehog plan, but it's his best chance for counterplay in the 5.c4 variation. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White defends his e4-pawn. Now that the e4-square is defended by a piece, White is threatening to play e5. }
6... Qc7 { Black defends the e5-square with his queen. } 7. a3
{ White prevents ...Bb4. Sidelines with ...Bb4 have been prevented, now Black is almost certain to play this in Hedgehog style. Other than preventing ...Bb4, a3 is a useful move to make in the Hedgehog because White wants to attack on the queenside. }
7... Nxe4
{ Black temporarily sacrifices a piece. He can win the piece back and keep his extra pawn, but this approach is risky because Black is behind in development. }
8. Nxe4 Qe5
{ Though Black goes up a pawn, his only developed piece is his queen. } 9. Bd3
{ 9.Qd3 allows 9...f5, winning the piece back. } 9... Qxd4 10. O-O
{ White has excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn in the form of his lead in development. White plans to develop all of his pieces rapidly  (possibly with tempo on Black's queen)  followed by an attack against Black's king. Even if an immediate attack doesn't succeed, White should still have good compensation for the sacrificed pawn due to his superior piece activity and Black's lack of a plan to consolidate  (he is many tempi behind on development)  , giving White long-term potential and attacking chances. }
