4. d4 Nf6 { The most flexible move. } 5. Nf3 c6
{ Black adds support to the d5-square and prevents Nb5. } 6. g3
{ White prepares to fianchetto his light-squared bishop. This approach is practical because White's pieces are well coordinated and White can claim a positional advantage  (due to his extra space and Black's exposed queen)  with normal developing moves. }
6... Bg4
{ Black develops his light-squared bishop to an active square, preparing to play ...e6 without locking it inside Black's pawn chain. The downside of this approach is that White can later target this bishop with h3, forcing Black to either retreat  (allowing g4 and Ne5 with the initiative)  or give up the bishop pair. Locking up Black's bishop with ...e6 would have been too passive, so Black didn't have much choice. }
7. Bg2
{ White fianchettoes his light-squared bishop and prepares to castle kingside. White can challenge Black's g4-bishop after he is more developed. }
7... e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Bf4 Qd8 10. h3
{ Now that White has castled and developed all of his minor pieces, he is ready to challenge Black's light-squared bishop. }
10... Bxf3 { 10...Bh5  11.g4  Bg6  12.Ne5 } 11. Qxf3
{ White has the advantage due to his bishop pair and superior piece activity.   11...Qxd4  12.Nb5   11...0-0  12.Ne2  Nbd7  13.c4 }
